WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.120
Hi everyone, my name is Cecil and I'm here with my colleague Jay and we're part of the

00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:16.520
Posit support team and today we're going to walk through the process of checking to make

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:21.400
sure that your launcher-sessions-callback-address is set correctly.

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:26.600
So the launcher-sessions-callback-address, if you have launcher enabled, is the address

00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:32.400
that each session talks back to the primary Workbench node with.

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:37.520
And if you have launcher enabled, it's a very important setting because if it's not set

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:43.799
correctly then the session won't be able to communicate back with the Workbench host.

00:00:43.799 --> 00:00:49.520
So there are a few ways to check if you've had this set correctly.

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:56.240
If it's set incorrectly and you click on the Workbench jobs tab, you should see a pop-up

00:00:56.240 --> 00:01:01.000
appear and there's a support article which walks through this but the pop-up looks like

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:02.000
this.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:07.440
So you'll see an error saying the Workbench jobs feature is not configured correctly and

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:10.879
to adjust this in your rserver.conf.

00:01:10.879 --> 00:01:19.040
So there is a test that we can use to see if our launcher-sessions-callback-address

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:27.599
is set correctly and that involves running a curl command to the jobs feature API which

00:01:27.599 --> 00:01:32.680
effectively checks if the launcher feature is enabled.

00:01:32.680 --> 00:01:37.440
And if it returns true, then we know that the launcher-sessions-callback-address is

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:39.040
set correctly.

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:44.839
If you see an error, then we know it's set incorrectly and it will need to be adjusted.

00:01:44.839 --> 00:01:48.000
And an example of this error is like this.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:54.559
So running that curl command will produce an error saying curl failed to connect to

00:01:54.559 --> 00:01:56.040
localhost.

00:01:56.040 --> 00:02:02.879
But if this is successful and we have a host here where it is set correctly, you can see

00:02:02.879 --> 00:02:05.879
that the result comes back as true.

